ing Is Everything -- tIntroduction -- tChapter Thirteen. Speed Versus Safety in Drug Development -- tChapter Fourteen. Overcoming “Premarket Syndrome” -- tChapter Fifteen. FDA’s Public Health Imperative -- tPART FIVE. Old and New Issues in Drug Regulation -- tIntroduction -- tChapter Sixteen. The Drug Efficacy Study and Its Manifold Legacies -- tChapter Seventeen. Drug Safety Communication -- tChapter Eighteen. Innovation Policy Failures in the Manufacturing of Drugs -- tPART SIX. Regulatory Exclusivities and the Regulation of Generic Drugs and Biosimilars -- tIntroduction -- tChapter Nineteen. From “Recycled Molecule” to Orphan Drug -- tChapter Twenty. FDA, Negotiated Rulemaking, and Generics -- tChapter Twenty-One. The “Follow-On” Challenge -- tChapter Twenty-Two. FDA Regulation of Biosimilars -- tPART SEVEN. New Wine in Old Bottles -- tIntroduction -- tChapter Twenty-Three. Analog Agency in a Digital World -- tChapter Twenty-Four. Twenty-First-Century Technology with Twentieth-Century Baggage -- tChapter Twenty-Five. Device-ive Maneuvers -- tChapter Twenty-Six. A New Regulatory Function for E-Prescriptions -- tChapter Twenty-Seven. Race and the FDA -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn its decades-long effort to assure the safety, efficacy, and security of medicines and other products, the Food and Drug Administration has struggled with issues of funding, proper associations with industry, and the balance between consumer choice and consumer protection. Today, these challenges are compounded by the pressures of globalization, the introduction of novel technologies, and fast-evolving threats to public health. With essays by leading scholars and government and private-industry experts, FDA in the Twenty-First Century addresses perennial and new problems and the improvements the agency can make to better serve the public good.The collection features essays on effective regulation in an era of globalization, consumer empowerment, and comparative effectiveness, as well as questions of data transparency, conflicts of interest, industry responsibility, and innovation policy, all with an emphasis on pharmaceuticals. The book also intervenes in the debate over off-label drug marketing and the proper role of the FDA before and after a drug goes on the market. Dealing honestly and thoroughly with the FDA's successes and failures, these essays rethink the structure, function, and future of the agency and the effect policy innovations may have on regulatory institutions abroad.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aDrugsxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Government & Business.2bisacsh1 aBarnes, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBierer, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoyd, Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarpenter, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCharo, R. Alta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, I. Glenn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, I. Glenn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCopeland, Katrice Bridges, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCortez, Nathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDevine, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDigilova, Alla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEnglish, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, Barbara J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/